AB  - The present study has explored teachers’ perspectives about students' cultural and linguistic diversity (CLD) coming from different cultural and linguistic backgrounds in Baluchistan and the effects of these perspectives on their approaches towards culturally responsive teaching practices. A survey questionnaire was administered to 122 secondary school English teachers, selected through a proportionate sampling technique. The responses of the participants were analyzed through descriptive and inferential statistics (Pearson correlation coefficient). Results of the study revealed that majority of the teachers were inquisitive and aware of the learning needs of CLD students at some extent, but they were less supportive to entertain the learning needs of culturally and linguistically diverse students. The respondents' perspectives show significant correlation with the culturally responsive teaching approaches. Considering the results, this study recommends that curriculum developers and policymakers develop instructional and cultural competencies in pre-service and in-service teachers' education programs. In addition, disjunction between recruitment policies for bilingual teachers and general education teacher needs to be revised. © 2021, TESOL International Journal. All Rights Reserved.
